<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>be a close call • be too close to call</xh5><p> <i>be a close call</i>—(also: be a close shave) said of a dangerous situation that a person just manages to avoid: Though he escaped with his life and his job, it was <u>a close call</u>.</p><p> <i>be too close to call—</i>said of the outcome of a competition, etc. that is very hard to judge: The horses came to the finish line in a dead heat, and, without a photograph, the results were <u>too close to call</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>be too close to home</b>—(also: be too close for comfort) dangerously nearby; affecting a person intimately: A crime that occurred <u>too close to home</u> still has its grip on Chief Inspector Alan Banks.</p> </entry>
